[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/DrHack"]
[UTCDate "2019.04.16"]
[UTCTime "23:16:35"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ The first thing to do here is to acknowledge that we are standing on the shoulders of greater people. In recent history, Alexander Kotov's book "Think Like a Grandmaster" boosted the chess population's general understanding of the selection process by providing a framework on which to build. Now 15 years later, the idea of candidate moves has been assimilated into the general ability of club players. The same can be said of A.J. Roycroft in his work on the iterative method of chess puzzle creation and solving in his 1972 publication, "Test Tube Chess" which is no longer in print. I am sure there are others that have fathered new concepts in move selection that I have either forgotten, or never known - so I give a nod to any old or new authors that I have omitted here.

I also have to acknowledge in this idiot's guide, that there are other idiots out there -just like me- who may have created a different method of move selection - especially when it comes to shorter time controls. I don't know what I don't know in regard to this. Sorry for my ignorance. }
 *


