{ Use this position as a self exploration exercise. Black to move. Don't just play a move. Be conscious about the moves that you consider, whether you ultimately select the move or discard it. On which part of the board are your eyes focused? Why?

Feel free to play moves to explore.. but be prepared to be insulted by my rhetoric. }
16... Qxh2+ { Nailed it. } (16... Bxg3 { Holy crap.. are you even trying? }) (16... O-O-O { Well.. your king is safe-ish I guess. You may have missed an opportunity to checkmate white. }) (16... Bf3 { Do you even chess bro? }) (16... Qg2+ { Do you even chess bro? Lookie at the Knighties. Ouchie. }) (16... hxg3 { And now white defends his king across the 2nd rank after fxg2. Black is down a piece. }) (16... Ng4 { Hanging a knight probably won't help you win. }) 17. Kxh2 hxg3+ { Bam! That's kicking it up a notch! } (17... Ng4+ { You should take a mulligan. Your knight died a horrible and purposeless death... alone in the desert of g4... nobody heard his screams... ok.. thats enough. Try again. }) (17... Bxg3+ { No.. This unfortunate move leads to a safe white king (after Kg1), and a missing black queen. Tip your king over and thank him for the game. At least you tried. }) (17... Bf3 { What in the SAM HILL? }) 18. Kg1 { Mate in 1. } 18... Rh1# { Take a few seconds to consider how you solved this. Was it by trial and error or something more systematic? Did you think through all 3 moves (Qxh2, hxg3, and Rh1#) before starting to make moves or did you work out one move at a time? Did you consider other moves than Qxh2 first? What were they? Why do you think you left Qxh2 until later? } 0-1


