[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ This chapter is optional. Use the hints to navigate through it to skip.

When solving a position where one side is clearly superior to the other, the iterative solve method is useful. The below method may seem like a lot to take in, but each of the steps can be done very rapidly - sometimes in fractions of a second. We will break it down further in chapters 5-8.

Iterative Solve Method
1. Examine the material first without pawns, and then with pawns.
2. Examine the positional features.
3. Look for threats from your opponent.
4. Is the position clear enough to list defenses to the threats?
5. Look for your own threat(s).
6. Choose your opponent's responses to your threat(s).
7. Repeat Steps 3-7 as necessary.

This position is just for fun. I recommend trying some of these steps out to see if you can do it without further guidance. }
41. Rh8 { Rubinstein's First Choice. } (41. Nc4 { Pretty strong move there Hercules. Nc4 is the computer's number 1 choice. Well done! Check the hint to move on. }) (41. Rxd8+ { NOOPE!! Chuck Testa. ***Warning*** If you watch this video - you can't unsee it.. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LJP1DphOWPs }) (41. exf4 { This is a pretty good move. If black captures d4, the open e file will give him trouble. Check the hint to move on. }) (41. a4 { I'm not sure how to respond to this one. Try something more... well.. just more. }) (41. Rb1 { Repurposing the rook is a reasonable idea, but not very strong. }) (41. Rb6 { I see what you did there. No.. try something else. }) 41... fxe3 42. fxe3 { Rubinstein's first choice. With black unable to leave the defense of his b pawn, the game went downhill rapidly and ended on move 51. The full game is presented at the end of the study. Try a few more moves and then we will move on to break down the individual steps. } (42. Nc4 { Yes.. this is still strongest + you are amazing. Check the hint to see Akiba's choice. }) (42. Rxh4 { No... just no. }) (42. Nxc6 { I can see why you are here. You need help.. Try again. }) (42. Nb3 { Yes.. let's bring the knight back to block our rook. BRRRNF! }) 42... Kd7 43. Rg2 { With both white rooks attacking the king and knight, the game went downhill quickly. See Rubinstein vs Takacs at the end of the study. } (43. Rh2 { This move allows black to unwind his position after Nf7. Sure you get a pawn, but it would be nice to keep black's pieces out of the game. }) (43. Nb3 { Leaving pressure on b7 allows black's rook to re-enter the game. Try something else. }) 1-0


