[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Step 1: Examine the Material - first without pawns, then with pawns.

This step could be more difficult for a beginner if the material is more diverse. I assume the reader can do the basic addition using pawn = 1, Bishop =3, Knight = 3, Rook = 5, Queen = 9.

If you are a more advanced player, value your pieces based on utility and position. <-- If you have no idea what I just said.. don't do this.

Finding a material imbalance between the sides cues the solver to use different resources in solving the position. For example: If black is ahead +5, he is able to look over a move set that gives back some material and therefore has a wider range of options. Unfortunately, this goes a little beyond the scope of this study.

When I examine the material in this position, I find that the position is equal in terms of raw piece count, but black's pieces have more value than the usual count because of their utility and position. }
 0-1


