{ Step 2: Examine the positional features ->

Positional features were introduced to the world in Aron Nimzowitsch's work that was published in several pieces between 1925-1927 (thanks wiki) . They were eventually compiled into one manual that we know today as, "My System." After the 1930's, countless authors have revised and appended his list of what might be important in any given position. Other noteable authors to write on the subject include Sam Reshevsky, Boris Gelfand, and Jacob Aagard - to name just a few of the many!

Features of the above position:

1. Hanging knight on g4.

2. The black bishops are aimed at the white king's position.

3. The black rooks are covering the open files, c and d.

4. Black has tension on the white bishop at e4 and the white knight at c3 -> Meaning he could capture them if he chooses to do so.

5. The white king is in a mating net (has 0 useful squares).

The positional features seem to be hinting at some kind of king's side action - or perhaps something through the c and d files - or a combination of both. }
 *


