[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/DrHack"]
[FEN "2rr2k1/1b2qppp/pb2p3/1p2P3/1P2BPn1/P1N5/1B2Q1PP/R4R1K b - - 4 21"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Step 4: Is the position clear enough to list defenses to the threats? Yes.

***There are three ways to save a hanging piece. 1. Move it. 2. Defend it. 3. Trade it. 4. Make a counter-threat or capture an equal or greater value piece. (I can't count.. don't worry about it)***

The moves that appear in our defensive move set are: 21. ...Nh6 (move it), 21. ...Ne3 (move it), 21. ...h5(defend it) 21. ...Nf2+ (trade it), 21. ...Bxe4 (make an equal or greater counter-threat) 21. ...Qh4 (defend it)

***Explore each of the defensive moves to reveal steps 5 and 6. Try Qh4 last as this will advance the study.

Defensive Moves:
21. ...Nh6
21. ...Ne3
21. ...h5
21. ...Nf2+
21. ...Bxe4
21. ...Qh4 <--- exploring this move advances the study. }
21... Qh4 { Rubinstein's first choice. Note that there was a stronger move not listed in the previous comments - 21. ...Nxh2. I'll leave that one to the reader to figure out. } (21... Nxh2! { No, stop being difficult... Explore the moves in the text to the left there. Good move, by the way! White can certainly not recapture the knight or he will be mated on the next move. This is the computer's favorite move. What is the follow up after 22. Qh5! }) (21... Nh6?! { Step 5: Look for black's threats after playing this move. There are none... Step 6: Play the response to black's threat: White can play whatever it wants, there is no threat. }) (21... Ne3 $19 { Step 5: Your threats? Black now threatens Nxf1, and also Bxe4 followed by Rc2! Step 6: The dual threat has only one sufficient answer. 22. Bxb7 followed by moving the rook away from f1. }) (21... h5 { Step 5: Black's threats did not change on this move. Everything that was threatened is still threatened, and white gets another turn to try to solve the position. This is a good move since black's threats are unavoidable, but does not advance the position. Let's give it a B+ and move on. }) (21... Nf2+?! { Step 5: Black threatens to play Nxe4. Step 6: White will trade his rook for two minor pieces after Rxf2 to avoid this threat. }) (21... Bxe4 { Step 5: Black has created a counter-threat or capture. White will have to regain his material or play behind. Step 6: List white's responses. 22. Qxe4, 22. Qxg4, 22. Nxe4.
***Rinse and repeat Step 3-6. Eventually we will come to a moment in each line where the material is no longer equal and we can evaluate the position as better or worse.***
22. Qxg4 Bf5 - The white queen is in zug. All her moves are bad for one reason or another. Explore the position more in the game file at the end of the study.
22. Qxe4 - Find mate in 4.
22. Nxe4 - Black's best here is probably just to take the h2 pawn. White can not recapture the knight due to checkmate. Black is +1. } 22. Qxg4 (22. Nxe4 { White's best attempt. The white knight defends some of the attacking possibilities for black. Black's best is now to just win the pawn with Nxh2. }) (22. Qxe4 { Find Mate in 4. } 22... Qh4 23. h3 Qg3 24. hxg4 Qh4#) 22... Bf5 { The white queen is in zugzwang. It can move, but all the moves are bad. Feel free to explore further on your own. }) 22. g3 { Use the iterative process to solve this position from step 3:
3. Look for threats from your opponent.
4. Is the position clear enough to list defenses to those threats?
5. Look for your own threat(s).
6. Choose white's responses to your threat(s).
7. Repeat Step 3-6 as necessary. } 22... Rxc3 { That's it! Removing one of the defenders of e4. Note that the white queen is overworked defending both e4 and h2. } (22... Qh3 { Your bishop sir! }) (22... Qh5 { Your bishop sir! }) (22... Qxh2+ { Well, at least you held the status quo. Unfortunately, this doesn't really win the game. BUT it also doesn't lose the game after 23. Qxh2 Bxe4+ 24. Nxe4 Nxh2 25. Kxh2 Rc2+ forking the king and bishop at b2. }) (22... Rd2 { Yaargh!! Well.. many pirate charges ended the same way - a brilliant flurry and then a horrid death. You've lost a rook. Try again. }) (22... Bxe4+ { Hey! Not bad. You saved the bishop from certain doom and now you have time to save the queen. There's a better move though.. so crap. }) (22... Rc7 { Your queen sir! }) (22... Rd7 { Your queen sir! }) 23. gxh4 Rd2 { It is forced mate from here. The queen may not move away or Rxh2#. Qxd2 is forced. If white tries the computer defense Rf2, black can capture the bishop at e4 for a nice knight forking combination - Bxe4 Qxe4 Nxf2+!! } (23... Rc2 { uh.. no. If you are trying to remove the defender of e4, you'll have to try harder. }) (23... Bxe4+ { After Qxe4 you are probably losing. How will you give the final check? }) (23... Rh3 { Your bishop sir! }) (23... Re3 { Ya.. sort of like that. But not. QxR and you are not quite getting check mate. }) 24. Qxd2 Bxe4+ { Naturally. } (24... Rb3 { What is this even?! Call an ambulance for your bishop, it just got clobbered. }) (24... Rh3 { Your bishop sir! }) (24... Re3 { Your bishop is going to need an ambulance, after he clobbers it. }) 25. Qg2 Rh3 { Tada! White resigns. } (25... Rc2 { Yes. This wins. Rubinstein played a different rook move. }) (25... Bxg2+ { NOOOOO. His king will get away! All things considered, you might still be ahead, but an early checkmate would make things easier on yourself. }) 0-1


[Event "Vienna"]
