[FEN "r3kb1r/p1q1pppp/2n2n2/1p6/1PN3b1/P3PN2/1B3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ **Solve this position for fun**

Many bloggers and chess enthusiasts have written on the subject of candidate moves in the last 15 years after GM Kotov made it popular. I have to give the nod and wink to those experts and enthusiasts. The reader will easily be able to follow up with a google search or two to find more information (or complete crap, depending on which link you click first). The candidate move selection process has two main components:

1. Fill out a list of candidate moves.
2. Evaluate each candidate move until it reaches a position that is clearly favoring one side, or can be judged equal.

Give the position a try **JUST FOR FUNSIES**, and then we will break the process down in the next few chapters. }
11. Nce5 { Your orthogonal hopper has played with impudence. Congratulations, this is Rubinstein's first choice. } (11. Be5 { Heh. Heh. I'm not laughing at you per se.. I'm laughing at your hanging stuff after 11. ...Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qc3+! Which wins the white rook or knight. DOH! }) (11. Na5 { Not terrible. You didn't let him capture your knight, that was smart. Try for a smarter move. }) (11. Ncd2 { Not terrible! You didn't let him capture your knight, that was smart. Try for a smarter move. }) (11. Be2 { Your knight sir! }) (11. Nb6 { Do you even chess? }) (11. Nd6+ { Do you even chess? }) (11. h3 { Well.. thats a counter threat, sort of. What if he takes your knight at f3, and then captures your other knight at c4 next? You lose a piece. Try again. }) 11... Nxe5 12. Nxe5 { Holy Carpe Move - ium!! You got it. } (12. Bxe5 { Not bad. Makes for a symmetrical game after Qd7. How are you planning to get ahead? }) (12. Rc1 { Hmm.. after Nc4 black is going to be all over your position like fire ants on a roast ham. That's delicious. Plus.. you are down a piece. Let's try again. }) 12... Bxd1 13. Bxb5+ { YAHTZEE! } (13. Rxd1 { You failed to recover a queen's worth of material. Try again. }) (13. Kxd1 { Oh.. Black is up a queen. Here is a short video to help you see the humor in the situation as your king is stuffed and mounted.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LJP1DphOWPs }) 13... Nd7 14. Bxd7+ (14. Nxd7 { There is a tactic here for black. I don't blame you for not spotting it! Black can try 14. ...Be2 which attacks the b5 bishop and makes the discovery fruitless. On 15. Kxe2 Qc2+ 16. Ke1 a6!! The white bishop will be under attack and the discovery will be meaningless. Nice try. }) (14. Rxd1 { YES. Nailed it. Rubinstein found a different and equally good move. So if you want to be like him, you'll have to try again. }) 14... Qxd7 { After 14. ...Kd8, white would win easily after Rxd1, threatening to checkmate on the next move with Nf7. } 15. Nxd7 { Very nice!! White is up a pawn and cruising to a better middle game. Well done! } 1-0


