[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/DrHack"]
[FEN "3r1rk1/pp3ppp/1np1p3/q7/3P4/1QP1PPP1/P3BP2/R4RK1 w - - 1 18"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Listing candidate moves is a process that can be done differently based on the players taste. I'm not necessarily talking about the tendency of newer players to make incomplete lists, nor the tendency to create lists that are too big to fully explore before the clock expires. Those two common mistakes are important, but not to the point of how this process is done.

-->One chess master might make a thorough list of candidate moves and then explore that list, while another might make a partial list, and then add moves to the list where other creative ideas present themselves during analysis. The method of building the list is somewhat unique to play style. }
 1-0


[Event "Training Move Selection (Interactive): Thorough List vs Creative List"]
[Date "2019.04.18"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Training Move Selection (Interactive)"]
[ChapterName "Thorough List vs Creative List"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/jutEaR9r/SxGWCYtF"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/DrHack"]
[FEN "3r1rk1/pp3ppp/1np1p3/q7/3P4/1QP1PPP1/P3BP2/R4RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.04.18"]
[UTCTime "00:50:22"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ The thorough mind may tackle the problem of making a list of candidate moves by adding all relevant moves and then systematically ticking them off until a sufficient idea is found. In the position - an inclusive list may look like this:

18. Rab1
18. Kg2
18. c4
18. Rfc1
18. Qb4
18. Qc2
18. Rfd1
18. a4
18. Bd3
18. f4

If the above list is a complete list of the useful moves in the position - then the creative method will only pull a sub-set of the complete list. See below:

A more creative undertaking of the candidate move list can start with a question - "How do I aim more stuff at the king" or "How do I attack this pawn, piece or square." or simply, "How do I improve this piece."

For example: If white asks himself, "How do I attack and pressure b7." His candidate move list will be much shorter than the complete list:

18. Rab1
18. Rfb1
18. f4 - preparing Bf3

As these three moves are explored, white may find that he would like to make the knight move from b6 and so he might expand his list to add 18. c4 - planning to push to c5.

When a player deems none of these moves in his candidate list help his position, he may discard the whole set and ask a new question. For example: How can I attack the king's side? The move set for this question may look more like this:

18. Kg2 - preparing Rh1
18. Bd3
18. Qc2

You can have prophylactic questions like: How do I stop my opponent from playing e5?

18. f4 - the only move that accomplishes this.

As you can see, the question asked when using a selective (or creative) method of candidates drives the moves explored, which changes the path of the game. Stronger players ask better questions of the position.

Move on to the next Chapter. }
 *


