[FEN "3r1rk1/pp3ppp/1np1p3/q7/3P4/1QP1PPP1/P3BP2/R4RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.04.18"]
[UTCTime "02:28:43"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ In the evaluation phase - the general idea is to look forward in each position until the player is sure that he is either ahead, behind, or equal to his opponent in the coming positions. This requires a method of evaluating a position!

Ok let's get into evaluating each candidate move on this list:

1. Rab1
2. Rfc1
3. Kg2
4. Qb4
5. Qc2
6. a4
7. c4
8. f4

Evaluate on your own and then play each move to see my evaluation (backed up by computer analysis). Play f4 last, as this move will advance the study. }
1. f4 { Part of the plan to pressure b7. This is white's strongest plan, and f4 is a critical part of that plan - to stop e5 and also prepare Bf3. This may be the strongest move in the position - and Akiba's first choice! } (1. Rab1 { This move is a part of the strongest plan, which is an attack on b7. Black must play e5 or c5 if he wishes to play actively. The pressure to b7 creates an immobile knight on b6. It is hard to quantify this position, but if black does not have tactical counter-play we can probably guess that white is equal or better. }) (1. Rfc1 { Banking on black's attempt to play actively. Black needs to play e5 or c5 to break white's space and punch a hole for the rooks to invade. This move is worth slightly less than Rab1 - but does not diminish white's position in any way. }) (1. Kg2 { Starting an attacking idea at h7. This attempt is likely futile, however this move does not change white's positional edge which is the space that his center provides. This is worth slightly more than Rfc1 probably because of the increased rook activity on the h file. }) (1. Qb4 { Trading queens and blocking the b file with a pawn - removing all pressure to black's position. This is not a good idea positionally. White may be ahead a small amount or equal. Black's plan to attack the center is still clear, while white has a less clear path than he did last move. }) (1. Qc2 { Removing the pressure to black's position at b7. The knight is free to move. Pawn moves to c5 or e5 are still possible to poke at white's center. Qc2 does not improve the position, and the game is probably equal now, or slightly in black's favor because black's plan is less complicated to play than it was last turn. }) (1. a4 { Discouraging black from playing c5, due to Qb5 (Removing the queen's gives white pressure to a7 and likely wins a pawn. On Qxc3 white will play dxc5 and capture the b7 pawn). Black might still try to poke the center with e5, so this move doesn't really slow down black's plan. It keeps the status quo, white is probably ahead still. }) (1. c4 { Not good. This move gives black an easier road to the central breaks - and white has less defense of d4. }) 1... c5 { Come up with your own list of candidates, and then play the strongest. Good luck! } 2. Bf3 { Rubinstein's first choice. } (2. dxc5 { What an unfortunate move. Black has counter-play against the isolated c pawn. Try again. }) (2. a4 { Great move! Not Akiba's favorite though. Use the hint feature to move on since you've nailed it! }) (2. Kg2 { Changing plans? Let's stick with the queen's side pressure for now. }) 2... Rd7 3. a4 { YES! The pressure on the queen's side continues to build, now white controls b5 and is able to place a queen there. } (3. Rfc1 { I'm not sure if the c file will ever open. That's a big maybe. Try again. }) (3. Rab1 { Hopeful that you can make his knight move? There are better ideas. }) (3. Kg2 { Pretty good idea. Let's stick to the plan on the queen's side though. Try again. }) 3... Nd5 4. Rfc1 { Needed some defense, didn't it? NICE MOVE! } (4. c4 { Very good move. Not Akiba's favorite though because it leaves a hole at b4 for black's knight. Try defending c3 instead. }) (4. Bxd5 { Meh. Your bishop was the better piece. The game will probably enter a pure rook ending from here. }) 4... g6 5. Qb5 { Forcing the queens off the board. Now the pressure to a2 will be meaningful. } 5... Qxb5 6. axb5 { Noice. } 6... cxd4 7. cxd4 { Yes! Opening the c file for the rook to play. } (7. exd4 { Also good, but leaves a backwards pawn at c3. This may be less favorable than having everything well defended. }) 7... b6 $16 { White is slightly better. He has a permanent target on a7 and holds the tension on black's knight. } *


